{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"a1d591f6-b0ee-4413-a384-bc01ca952f6c","content":"Here's what I found in `my_app/views.py`:\n\n**`datetime.now()` — line 3**\n```\nnow = datetime.now()\n```\n\nThis is an **untestable static call** — you can't control the clock in tests, making time-dependent assertions brittle or impossible.\n\n### Recommended fix\n\nUse Django's `django.utils.timezone.now()` (timezone-aware and mockable), and inject it or mock it in tests:\n\n```python\nfrom django.utils import timezone\n\ndef index(request):\n    now = timezone.now()\n    return render(request, 'index.html', {'time': now})\n```\n\nThen in tests you can freeze time with `unittest.mock.patch` or [`freezegun`](https://github.com/spulec/freezegun):\n\n```python\nfrom unittest.mock import patch\nfrom django.utils import timezone\n\nwith patch.object(timezone, 'now', return_value=datetime(2026, 1, 1)):\n    response = client.get('/')\n```\n\nThat's the only instance in this project. The codebase is small — just the one file.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"0e327089-c4bd-4663-8c99-8536c76d095b","outputTokens":267,"requestId":"CFC6:2E7D56:17006D5:1AFEC17:69EC2847"},"id":"52fd4d8f-834b-45b5-bf7c-e307704da1b8","timestamp":"2026-04-25T02:34:54.097Z","parentId":"7688ef2c-4513-4aca-b471-4904c9a2b7c5"}
